# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1881-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1881 throughout the world.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1881-in-baseball] Inter-league playoff: New York Mets (ECA) defeat Chicago (NL), 2 games to 1.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1882-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1882 throughout the world.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1883-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1883 throughout the world.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1884-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1884 throughout the world.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1884-in-baseball] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1884-in-baseball] Old Hoss Radbourn won a record 59 or 60 games (depending on the sources), a record that will almost certainly never be broken.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1884-in-baseball] In addition to wins, Radbourn led the National League in games (75), games started (73), complete games (73), ERA (1.38), saves (2), strikeouts (441), and innings pitched (678.2).
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1884-in-baseball] The season record for pitching strikeouts (369, by Tim Keefe 1883) is broken by seven players, with Hugh Daily beating Keefe's record by 114.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1884-in-baseball] To this day (as of 2020), six of the top ten strikeout seasons were accomplished in 1884 (including five of the top seven).
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1884-in-baseball] 1884 was the first season in which pitchers were allowed to throw overhand.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1885-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1885 throughout the world.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1885-in-baseball] Post-season playoff: the Chicago White Stockings played the St.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1885-in-baseball] Louis Browns, which ended with both teams going 3–3–1 in a best-of-seven series.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1885-in-baseball] Game 1 finished in a tie called after eight innings due to darkness; Game 2 was awarded to Chicago by forfeit after six innings because St.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1885-in-baseball] Louis refused to continue after disputing an umpiring decision.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1885-in-baseball] Both teams dispute the series and claim the championship.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1886-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1886 throughout the world.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/1887-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1887 throughout the world.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] Taylor was born in 1855 in Washington, D.C.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] He started his professional baseball career in 1879 with the Northwestern League's Dubuque Red Stockings.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] The following year, he played for San Francisco of the California League.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] In 1881, Taylor had stints with three teams in the National League.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] He made his major league debut on May 21 with the Worcester Ruby Legs, played six games for them, then appeared in one game for the Detroit Wolverines, and then appeared in 24 games for the Cleveland Blues.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] Mostly playing in the outfield, he batted .222 that year.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] Taylor spent 1882 and 1883 with the American Association's Pittsburgh Alleghenys.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] He had arguably his best hitting season in 1882 when – splitting his time between five positions – he batted .281 and ranked third in the league with a .452 slugging percentage.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] In 1883, Taylor batted .260 and also appeared in 19 games as a pitcher.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] He led the league with nine games finished and went 4–7 with a 5.39 earned run average.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] Taylor joined the new Union Association in 1884 as a member of the St.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] Louis and went 25–4 on the mound with a 1.68 ERA in 263 innings.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] He ranked third in the league in wins, third in winning percentage, second in ERA, and first in saves (4).
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] In July, however, Taylor jumped to the American Association's Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] He pitched 260 more innings for Philadelphia, compiling an 18-12 record there with a 2.53 ERA.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] Taylor's 523 innings pitched in 1884 ended up being more than half of his major league career total of 799.2, and he never pitched more than 127 innings in any other season.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] Taylor pitched six games for the Athletics in 1885, going 1–5.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] Joining the Baltimore Orioles in 1886, his record was even worse, at 1–6.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] Taylor also played in the Southern Association that year and went 3–7 while batting .100.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] In 1887, he went 7–3 and batted .269 for the Eastern League's New Haven Blues.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] He also pitched (and won) one game for the Athletics on August 16, which was his final major league appearance.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] Taylor then ended his career with two seasons in the minors.
[src:billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher/billy-taylor-1880s-pitcher] Taylor died in Jacksonville, Florida, in 1900.
